issue.title: Extend float16 converter api with auto_mixed_precision

repository.name: onnxmltools
repository.description: ONNXMLTools enables conversion of models to ONNX

body: @xiaowuhu can you work on this please?

> @xiaowuhu can you work on this please?

sure, let me try.
@xadupre can you assign the issue to @xiaowuhu ? (I don't have permission)

The CPU EP may be inserting a lot of cast operations under the hood if the CPU op implementations don't support FP16, but it does seem bad that it's so much slower.
Not sure how to find that out other than reading the ORT source code or talking to someone on ORT team.

I will ask tingyeqiaqia about the inference speed. already contact with him yesterday through email.

A quick question, In general, fp16 is going to use in CPU device or GPU device?

By using auto_mixed_precision.py:

1. In CPU environment (provider=CPU-EP)

- the fp16 model can be converted, spent 129 seconds
- inference:  
    - fp32 model, 17 seconds.  
    - fp16 (auto_mixed_precision) model: 26 seconds. Result is correct.
    - fp16 (convert_to_float16) model: 26 seconds. Result is correct.


2. In GPU environment (provider=CUDA-EP)

- [this](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxconverter-common/commit/83ce3545a3b2c9458290bb68e09785977dea90a5) one not released, so need to manually fix the "missing providers" issue

- the fp16 model can be converted, spent 700 seconds, by checking 51 rounds
- inference
    - fp32 model, 4 seconds 
    - fp16 model (auto_mixed_precision): 3.3 seconds, Result is correct.
    - fp16 model (convert_to_float16): 3.3 seconds, But the Result is NaN.

3. about the model size.  I think it is big enough. the fp32 model have to use external data to avoid large than 2 GB. the fp16 model is about 680M. If you can share me some bigger model, I can have another try.

@garymm @BowenBao   what do you think for next step?

It seems like you've done the first 2 points in the original issue description, except maybe confirming that auto_mixed_precision can also **write** large models. Is that correct?
If so, then confirm that it can both read and write large models.
Then do the third point from the issue description.
